Introduction¶

Introduce the dataset:

This data set contains the customer's data from a fictional loan company - Prosper. This dataset comprises of 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The Prosper dataset contains 113937 observations and 81 variables. Out of these 81 variables, the analysis would be focused on just 17 variables of interest to help with answering the research questions. A new dataset with the variables of interest was created with a structure of 106312 observations and 17 features. The loan dataset includes nine categorical variables comprising of : ListingCreationDate, LoanStatus, ListingCategory, EmploymentStatus, IsBorrowerHomeowner, IncomeRange, IncomeVerifiable, LoanOriginationDate, LoanOriginationQuarter and eight quantitative variables comprising of : Term, BorrowerAPR, BorrowerRate, LenderYield, EmploymentStatusDuration, StatedMonthlyIncome, LoanOriginalAmount, MonthlyLoanPayment.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest from the prosper dataset are - factors that affect a loan's outcome status, factors that affects the borrower's APR or interest rate, and ascertaining if there are differences between loans depending on how large the original loan amount was?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The LoanStatus, BorrowerAPR, BorrowerRate, LoanOriginalAmount are the main features in the dataset that i expect that upon investigation with other variables would give rise to the insights needed from the data. However, I think that the ListingCategory, IncomeRange, StatedMonthlyIncome, EmploymentStatus and IsBorrowerHomeOwner will have an effect on how large the original loan is as I think these are the main factors that can either help or hinder someone from getting a loan.I also think the EmploymentStatus, ImcomeRange and StatedMonthlyIncome will have an effect on the LoanStatus as i think employed persons would have the financial bandwidth to repay their loans in due time as compared to an unemployed or low income earner.

For the BorrowerAPR/BorrowerInterest feature, a 36 & 60 month Term will likely have a higher BorrowerInterest rate than a loan with Term of 12 months.Alternatively, Term of loan will have no considerable effect on the BorrowerAPR rate.

With respect to the loanOriginalAmount obtained by borrowers, loan amount of less than $10,000 will have higher BorrowerAPR and BorrowerInterest rate while loan amounts of greater than $20,000 will have lower BorrowerAPR/BorrowerInterest rates.

For the LoanOriginalAmount feature, it was observed that January and December had the highest sizes of loans on average, while June has the smallest sizes of loans. Also higher sizes of loans are deemded to be longer Term loans than smaller sizes of LoanOriginalAmount.

Interestingly, it was observed that borrowers of $0 income range had access to higher sizes of loans than borrowers in the income range of Not Employed and $1-$25,000 and also had access to same sizes of loans with those within the IncomeRange of $25,000-$50,000. Borrower with the income range of $25,000-100,000+ had access to the highest sizes of loans. Also, Employment status had an effect on LoanOriginalAmount obtained as employed borrowed access higher loans than the not employed/part-time borrowers.

For the LoanStatus outcome feature, a 36 month Term was observed to be prevalent as the majority Term in the Completed, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress and PastDue categories of loan statuses

With respect to the LoanOriginalAmount, completed loan status accessed the lowest sizes of loans (averaging $6000) while current loan status had access to the highest sizes of loans (averaging $10,500), all the categories of Past Due & Defaulted loan statuses showed no considerable difference in the original loan amount accessed

Conclusions¶

The Prosper loan dataset provided a large amount of variables when downloaded which was wrangled for the purpose of this analysis into seventeen(17) variables. We went further to carry out some data wrangling including data cleaning and data manipulation and in the course of this wrangling, two(2) additional variables were created - LoanOriginationMonth and LoanOriginationYear.

Three major questions guided the entire exploration and analysis of the loan dataset which are:

. What factors affects a loan's outcome status . What affects the borrower's APR or borrower interest rate . Are there differences between loans depending on how large the original loan amount was?

Based on these research questions, we identified FOUR(4) main variables of interest namely LoanStatus, BorrowerAPR, BorrowerInterest and LoanOriginalAmount. and some other predictor variables namely: Term, ListCategory, IncomeRange, StatedMonthlyIncome, EmploymentStatus, IsBorrowerHomeOwner, LoanOriginationQuarter, LoanOriginationMonth and LoanOriginationYear.

We then proceeded to carry out an exploratory analysis with univariate visualizations, bivariate visualizations, and multivariate visualizations of all the main and predictor variables to garner insights with regards to the research questions. The following insights formed the basis of the answers to our research questions from the exploration plots and analysis made.

Loan Outcome status A loan outcome status is affected by a variety of factors such as the loan Term which is the length of the loan. The Term of the loan however is dependent on the LoanOriginalAmount as smaller loan amounts get smaller loan Terms and vice versa. It was observed that loan Term OF 12 months has a higher rate of being completed, as it was observed that most of the loan status on PastDue were majorly of Term 36 and 60 months. Another factor that affects the loan outcome status is the LoanOriginalAmount. It was observed that higher loan amounts are more prone to have loan status of Defaulted, or PastDue while lower loan amounts had a higher rate of been completed.

Borrower APR & Borrower Interest The BorrowerAPR and BorrowerInterest rate were both assessed interchangeably in relation to other variables here. A careful observation of the exploration plots showed that Term and LoanOriginalAmount when combined has an interesting effect on the borrower's annual percentage rate (APR). Lower loan amounts of less than $10,000 and of a 12 month Term will definitely have lower BorrowerAPR rates. This is a great insight that can help prospective borrowers targeting short term loans with lower annual percentage rates to make a decision on the loan amount to apply for at Prosper. However, this is in constract with our observation when only the relationship between the BorrowerAPR and the LoanOriginalAmount is checked without any reference to the Term. It is seen that Loan original amounts greater than $20,000 are much more prone to have lower Borrower APR and Borrower Interest Rate compared to lesser amount of $10,000 and below which are more likely to have higher Borrower APR and Borrower Interest Rate thus demonstrating a negative correlation albeit a weak one. On the other hand, when the relationship of BorrowerAPR and Term are compared, Term has a positive correlation with borrower interest rate(Borrower Rate) and a negative correlation with BorrowerAPR. Our findings shows Term having a strong positive effect on BorrowerRate showing that a 36 and 60 month Term would have a higher BorrowerRate than a loan of a 12 month Term. while a closer assessment for the Borrower APR for all loans shows that although there is no considerable effect of Term on Borrower APR, loans with a 36 month term on average still have a slightly higher Borrower APR rates than a 12 and 60 month Term.

Loan Original Amount In ascertaining if there are differences between loans depending on the size of original loan, a couple of variables were checked.

Firstly, with respect to the LoanOriginationYear and LoanOriginationMonth, the progression of loans obtained across months of the year shows that higher loan amounts are gotten by borrowers in January and December than in other periods of the year, with June been the month with the lowest loan amounts given out on average.

Secondly, with respect to the Term, it was observed that higher sizes of loans are deemed to be longer Term loans than smaller sizes of LoanOriginalAmount. Larger loan original amounts of $12,000 and above would likely have a 60 month loan Term , while loan amounts of $7,500 on average would likely have a 36 month Term, with lesser amounts of $5,000 and below having a 12 month loan Term period to run.

Thirdly, with respect to the BorrowerIncomeRange, borrowers with the income range of $50,000-100,000+ had access to the highest sizes of loans. More interestingly, it was also observed that borrowers of $0 income range had access to higher sizes of loans than borrowers in the income range of Not Employed and $1-$25,000 and also had access to same sizes of loans with those within the IncomeRange of $25,000-$49,999. On a more deeper dive into why this could occur, we compared the IncomeRange with the EmploymentStatus and found out that borrowers of $0 income range within our data when accessed for their *EmploymentStatus* have patterns of *full-time, part-time* or *self-employed* employment statuses. This is an interesting observation that explains why they could access same sizes of loans as those in the $25,000-$49,999 income range bracket.

Furthermore, with respect to EmploymentStatus, it was observed that employed borrowers accessed higher loans sizes than the NotEmployed/part-time borrowers.

Lastly, when compared with MonthlyLoanPayment, it was observed that the higher the loan original amount obtained, the higher the monthly loan payments, signifying a positive correlation between MonthlyLoanPayment and LoanOrginalAmount across the different LoanStatus categories.
